POSTGRESQL REPLICATION
======================

This file contains the procedure for setting up PostgreSQL replication with
a single master and one or more standby servers.

1. Setup - all servers
2. Setup - master
3. Setup - standby servers
4. Failover
5. Shutting down standbys


SETUP - ALL SERVERS
===================

Two setup steps are necessary on all servers that will replicate or be
replicated: update pg_hba.conf, and install SSL cert/key files.

Add the following lines to pg_hba.conf to allow replication connections:

local      replication replication                  trust
hostssl    replication replication ::1/128          cert clientcert=1
hostssl    replication replication x.x.x.x          cert clientcert=1

Replace x.x.x.x with the NWS WAN block, or add multiple lines that each allow a
specific server. Every server in the replication cluster must be included in
this list.

All of the servers need to have the replication.crt and replication.key files
installed. These are the SSL cert and key that are required for replication
connections. You have to create these files yourself, except for root.crt which
must be the same file as /awips2/database/ssl/root.crt. Put them here:

/awips2/database/ssl/replication/${hostname -s}/replication.crt
/awips2/database/ssl/replication/${hostname -s}/replication.key
/awips2/database/ssl/replication/${hostname -s}/root.crt


SETUP - MASTER
==============

On the master server (the initial server that the others will replicate from),
run create-replication-role.sh to create the 'replication' database role.

The master also needs additional lines in postgresql.conf. If the server was
correctly identified as a central registry server at the time the
awips2-database-server-configuration RPM package was installed, then it should
not be necessary to manually add these lines, as the config file specific to
central registry will include them. You should check postgresql.conf anyway to
make sure they are there.

    max_wal_senders = 5
    wal_keep_segments = 64
    promote_trigger_file = '/awips2/database/data/promote'
    hot_standby = on
    include_if_exists = 'postgresql.standby.conf'


SETUP - STANDBY SERVERS
=======================

You must run "setup-standby.sh" on each server to turn it into a standby.

Before you run it, open the script in a text editor, and verify
the value of each variable in the Configuration section at the top of the
script.

When you run it, specify the master server as the first argument, e.g.:

  $ sudo ./setup-standby.sh dds1-ancf

The existing PostgreSQL data directory on the new standby server will be
destroyed, and it will become a replica of the master. pg_hba.conf will
be retained (i.e., will not be replaced with the copy from master).

Note that a standby can replicate from another standby--it does not have to
replicate directly from the master. This is useful for reducing WAN traffic.


FAILOVER
========

To promote a standby to master:

  1. Stop PostgreSQL on the master if it is running.
  2. On the standby, create the file "/awips2/database/data/promote" as the
     "awips" user. The standby will stop replication and recognize itself as
     the new master. Instead of creating the trigger file, it is also
     possible to trigger promotion by running, as the "awips" user:
         pg_ctl promote -D /awips2/database/data
  3. Delete /awips2/database/data/postgresql.standby.conf on the new master so
     that it does not attempt to replicate from some other server when
     it is restarted.
  4. On the old master and the other standbys, run setup-standby.sh with the
     hostname of the new master, to re-initialize them and start replicating
     from the new master.


SHUTTING DOWN STANDBYS
======================

Standby servers may not respond to shutdown requests via systemctl while in
recovery mode (that is, while streaming from the master). In that case the
server can still be shut down normally using pg_ctl:

    pg_ctl stop -D /awips2/database/data
